<HEAD>

<TITLE>MacArthur's Genius Awards: Catharine Stimpson, Director-- CRC</TITLE>




</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<ul>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-pcs.gif">
</center>
<P>
<a href="pcs1-96.html">Back to "MacArthur's Genius Awards"</a>
<BR>
<I>CATHARINE STIMPSON, 
<P>DIRECTOR, MACARTHUR FELLOWS PROGRAM</I>
<P>
<P>Catharine Stimpson's story is typical of many 
left-wing women of her generation.  Born in 1936, she became 
a radical activist in the `60s. But as the era ended and as she 
has aged, her sights turned from the streets to the schools. 
Rising up the academic and philanthropic ladder, Stimpson 
has never abandoned her feminism or her animus toward 
conservatives.
<P>Stimpson joined the English department of Barnard 
College in 1963, where she remained until 1980, when 
she joined the English Department at Rutgers University.  In 
the mid-1980s, she became dean of the Rutgers graduate 
school, where she stayed until her appointment to the 
MacArthur Foundation in 1994.  She retains a house in Staten 
Island, New York, and is officially on leave from Rutgers.
<P>Stimpson's early writings are quite militant.  In a 
1974 essay, for example, she charged that the plight of women 
in America was analogous to that of blacks, because &quot;what 
the economy gives both women and blacks are menial 
labor, low pay, and few promotions.&quot;  She added that &quot;blacks 
and women also live in the wasteland of American 
sexuality&quot; because &quot;white men, convinced of the holy primacy 
of sperm, yet guilty about using it, angry at the loss of the 
cozy sanctuary of the womb and the privilege of childhood, 
have made their sex a claim to power and then used their 
power to claim control of sex.  In fact and fantasy, they 
have violently segregated black men and white women.&quot;
<P>In 1976, Stimpson, who has never married, moved in 
with another woman and  became what she called &quot;father/mother&quot; 
 and &quot;parenter&quot; to four children, none her own.  She 
also began work on her only novel, <I>Class Notes </I>(1979).  
The work describes a woman who, like Stimpson, grew up in 
a small town in the state of Washington in the late 1940s 
and 1950s.  Periodically Harriet Springer, Stimpson's 
heroine, confronts men who drink excessively, beat her, and 
warn her of the dangers of Communism and the United Nations. 
 Stimpson's heroine escapes this male torment by 
entering an effete Eastern women's college where she learns 
the delights of lesbian love. 
<P>Stimpson became a national figure after she became 
a dean at Rutgers.  She generally sided with the left, 
though she has always opposed speech codes and has 
attacked feminists who call for censorship.  As Cathy Young 
reported in <I>Heterodoxy</I>, Stimpson has said her ultimate 
goal was for &quot;a mutiracial, multicultural, multispecied world.&quot; 
<P>Stimpson's views towards conservatives are best 
expressed in her 1987 essay &quot;Nancy Reagan Wears a Hat: 
 Feminism and Its Cultural Consensus.&quot;  &quot;Right-wing 
conservatism could also appeal to fears,&quot; she wrote, &quot;to 
the fears of women that they would be vulnerable and 
helpless if men did not protect them economically; to the fears 
of men that they would be vulnerable and helpless if 
women did not submit to them; and to the fears of both men 
and women that the world would be wholly cruel, 
wholly pitiless, wholly formless, if it had neither havening 
homes nor nurturing mother figures.&quot;
<P>Stimpson has denied she has that much influence 
over who becomes a MacArthur Fellow. But, in a 1994 
interview with the <I>Chicago Tribune</I> she said that as 
program director, &quot;one of my responsibilities is to make sure 
activists are as much represented as academics.&quot;
<P>
<a href="pcs1-96.html">Back to "MacArthur's Genius Awards"</a>



</BODY>

