<html>
<head>
<title>CRC Foundation Watch Vol. I No. 10</title>
</head>
<body>
<a name="top">
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation bar" border="O" align="left" ISMAP></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><IMG ALT="Foundation Watch" src="/crc/images/hdr-fw.gif"></center>
<font size=+1><i>Foundation Watch Vol. I No.9</i></font><P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>November, 1996</B></FONT><p>
<center><font size=-1><a href="#1">Inside the Ford Foundation</a> | <a href="#2">Present at the Creation</a> | <a href="#3">Who do Ford's Hispanic Groups Represent</a> | <a href="#4">In Ford's Deep Pockets</a> 
| <a href="#5">Perpetuating Stereotypes</a> | <a href="#6">The Agenda Behind Ford's Agenda</a> 
| <a href="#7">George Anne Geyer's Americans No More: Is Citizenship Dead?</a> | <a href="#9">Ford Foundation's Board of Trustees</a> | <a href="#10">Letters to the Editor</a> </center> 
</font><hr>
<a name="1">
<center><h2>Inside the Ford Foundation's Plan to Split Apart America </h2>
<h3>by Linda Chavez and Jorge Amselle</h3></center>
<p>
The roots of the Ford Foundation's support for Hispanic political activism can be traced to the late McGeorge
Bundy, National Security Adviser to Presidents Kennedy and Johnson
and president of the Ford Foundation from 1966 to 1979.  A high-minded
Boston Brahmin eager to turn from badly advising Lyndon Johnson
on Vietnam war policy to establishing domestic social priorities,
Bundy concentrated his efforts at Ford on improving American education
and on ending racial discrimination. 
<P>
&quot;He came to the foundation determined
to put as much distance as possible between himself and the horror
in the Far East,&quot; Waldemar Neilsen said in his book <I>The
Golden Donors</I>, &quot;to achieve high visibility for himself
as a liberal domestic reformer.&quot; Bundy made a dramatic series
of grants to change the direction of the foundation quickly. He
funded direct action protests by community groups, voter registration
drives, and even some outreach programs to urban street gangs.
With the Ford Foundation on their side beneficiaries quickly becme
&quot;more strident in their demands and more involved in local
politics,&quot; according to Neilsen. Congressman Wright Patman
went to the House floor to ask, &quot;Does the Ford Foundation
have a grandiose design to bring vast political, economic, and
social changes to the nation?&quot; The answer was yes. What Neilsen
called Bundy's &quot;sneering contempt&quot; during congressional
hearings led Patman to place legal prohibitions on &quot;political
and propagandistic grants&quot; and restrictions on voter registration
projects.
<P>&quot;Henry Ford II was close to 'going crazy'
with Bundy's 'progressive' _ and to his mind _  wastrel politics,&quot;
writes Georgie Anne Geyer in her new book <I>Americans No More
</I>[see review by Robert Huberty on page 8]. &quot;Ford dealers
across the country were bitterly complaining to him that Bundy's
policies were ruining their businesses: Thousands of Americans
were refusing to buy Fords.&quot;
<P>
As I first  pointed out in my book, <I>Out
Of The Barrio</I> (NY: Basic Books, 1991) Ford repeated  a pattern
characteristic of the political trends of the 1960s and 70s and
Bundy's liberalism played straight into the hands of ethnic activists.
They exploited liberalism's well-meaning and expansive social
concerns by advancing an aggressive political agenda undermining
America's tradition of equal opportunity.  The new Hispanic organizations
were products of  the Ford Foundation and it must bear a heavy
burden of responsibility for their actions. The Ford Foundation
was the leading funder of Hispanic advocacy groups.
<P>
Bundy's interest in Hispanic politics arose
from a 1968 study that the Ford Foundation commissioned on Hispanics
in America.  This was originally an internal document that would
guide the foundation and help direct its agenda and grantmaking
to Hispanics. 
<P>
The report concluded that Mexican Americans
were disorganized and fragmented and in need of a national organization
to serve their social, economic and political needs.  Siobhan
Oppenheimer Nicolau, a former Ford Foundation program officer
who guided Ford's early decisions to fund Hispanic organizations,
stated in 1990 that foundation officials thought Mexican Americans
were unable to create and sustain a network of viable institutions.
 Why?  &quot;They lacked the strong network of religious institutions
that had nurtured black leadership.  They lacked visibility outside
the Southwest, and they lacked a history of slavery, a powerful
tool that had galvanized white guilt and support for the black
civil rights movement.&quot;
<P>
To this day Ford officials use the same rhetoric.
Susan Vail Berresford, current president of the Ford Foundation,
wrote in the October 14, 1996 <I>National Review</I>, &quot;Our
grants to Hispanic-led groups to strengthen their communities
and improve their level of participation in American society hardly
constitute an &quot;attack on American democracy.&quot;<BR>
<P>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
<a name="2">
<P>
<B>Present at the Creation</B>
<P>
Relying on these conclusions, the Ford Foundation decided 
to create two major Hispanic organizations.  In 1968 it established
the Mexican American Legal Defense and Education Fund (MALDEF)
which was intended to use lawsuits, and courtroom and legislative
 maneuvering to promote public policy. In fact, the organization
was a creature of the Ford Foundation, and as she wrote in response
to Berresford in the same issue of <I>National Review</I>, &quot;would
not exist without foundation funding.&quot;
<P>
In 1968, too,  Ford funded the Southwest
Council of La Raza as an organization coordinating other organizations
-- which later became the National Council of La Raza, described
as &quot;the Latino equivalent of the Urban League.&quot;
<P>
It was a still a creature of the Ford Foundation,
dependent on annual grants from New York City and unrepresentative
of Hispanic Americans.
<P>
In the nearly three decades since their establishment,
these organizations, MALDEF in particular, have played an enormous
role in shaping public policy toward Hispanics, on everything
from immigration to education to voting laws.  In 1975 MALDEF
was instrumental in amending the 1965 Voting Rights Act to force
jurisdictions with significant numbers of voters identified as
Hispanic to receive voting materials in Spanish.  Today, more
than 270 jurisdictions are affected by this requirement.  Under
the act, jurisdictions in Michigan and elsewhere are required
to print Spanish language ballots at considerable cost even though
practically no one uses them.
<P>
From 1968 to 1975, MALDEF pushed through bilingual
education programs and requirements across the country.  They
have trapped Hispanic students in what are essentially Spanish-language
maintenance and development programs.  A September 1996 poll of
Hispanic parents by the Center for Equal Opportunity shows that
the vast majority of Hispanics don't agree with groups like MALDEF
on bilingual education. [see box on p.4] This national survey
found that 63 percent of Hispanic parents say they want their
children to learn English as quickly as possible. Only 16.9% want
Spanish taught first. Over 80 percent want their children's academic
courses to be taught in English and not Spanish.  But the bilingual
education programs favored by MALDEF do just the opposite.  They
teach schoolchildren almost exclusively in Spanish throughout
grade school and sometimes through high school.
<P>
The Ford Foundation remains the largest single
source of funding for MALDEF and NCLR.  According to Geyer, NCLR
in 1989 received $590,000 from Ford, a major share of its $3.5
million budget that year.  In 1991 it received $1.25 million from
Ford.  From 1968 to 1990 Ford gave more than $9.6 million to NCLR
and $14.2 million to MALDEF.  Susan Vail Berresford, the Ford
Foundation's current president, was a keynote speaker at NCLR's
annual conference in Denver this past July.  She was given NCLR's
President's Award for her leadership and commitment to NCLR. 
With ten thousand participants, this was NCLR's largest conference,
and it featured sessions on issues like: How to defend affirmative
action. 
<P>
Yet, NCLR's growth has blunted some of its
ideological edge, at least when it comes to raising money, and
this has led to tensions within the organization.  Funding for
the Denver conference, which cost $1.2 million, left some activists
fuming.  Specifically, critics complained that NCLR should not
have accepted a $25,000 sponsorship fee from the Golden, Colorado-based
Coors Brewing Company.  Some conservative members of the Coors
family have supported proposals to make English the official language
of the United States and have opposed racial preference policies.
<P>
NCLR, however, has learned the political and
financial ropes, and it knows how to run its organization and
agenda along several tracks.  As Raul Yzaguirre, president of
NCLR -- and past Chairman of Independent Sector, a group founded
by Common Cause's John Gardner to promote networking for social
change among non-profits -- explained to a reporter for the <I>Denver
Post</I>:  &quot;We learned how to do things right.&quot; Yzaguirre
added. &quot;We analyzed public policy, earned a reputation the
hard way, as reasonable, hard&#173;minded, objective [people].
Developing friends on [Capitol] Hill, then moving on to new areas.&quot;
Yzaguirre denies that NCLR's competence in Washington lobbying
has put it out of touch with the average Hispanic.  He told the
<I>Post</I>,  &quot;Check the polls, on every issue -&#173; civil
rights, education, housing, equal access -&#173; we [Hispanics]
are together.&quot; 
<P>
But polling data shows that Hispanics are not united behind NCLR positions.
Nevertheless, Yzaguirre is among the organizers for a Columbus Day protest march in Washington
DC -- endorsed by the U.S. Catholic Conference, Congressional Hispanic
Caucus, and other organizations -- whose leader, Los Angeles activist
Juan Jose Guiterrez told <I>The Washington Post</I>, &quot;To
the best of my knowledge, the great majority of the American public
does not support a fascist police state.&quot;
<p>
Despite their ability to stage media events,
MALDEF, NCLR, and other Hispanic advocacy organizations funded
by the Ford Foundation are not directly accountable to the community
whose interests they purport to represent.  The Hispanic community
does not elect the members, officers, or board of these organizations,
most of which pursue their objectives with little public scrutiny.
 Because they are not membership organizations dependent on individual
contributions from the community at large, few Mexican Americans
can name these groups.  Their leaders are unknown despite their
influence on public policy affecting Hispanics.  The Hispanic
community does not control the funding of these groups and, most
importantly, it has virtually no say in the agenda they choose
to promote.  The Ford Foundation and other grantmakers have freed
these organizations from the need to be accountable to the communities
they are supposed to represent.  And they have created a cadre
of ethnic power brokers instead of identifying legitimate representatives
from the Hispanic community.
<P>
These groups believe they are on the cutting
edge of social change.  But the future they envision is one in
which Hispanics become wards of government permanently entitled
to public benefits because of their ethnicity.  Most  Hispanics,
like other groups before them, would choose to become part of
the mainstream. Instead, these groups speak of &quot;empowering&quot;
Hispanics by defining them as members of a protected class. They
want to empower Hispanic children by winning court battles that
will require them to be taught in Spanish for a society where
the best jobs go to those who speak, read, and write English well.
 They insist that the fortunes of middle&#173;class Hispanics
must be determined by the political battles over the most disadvantaged
Hispanics, making the former hostage to the latter.  Only the
lobbyists and activists who broker the policies of the welfare
state benefit from such strategies.
<P>
With $7.5 billion in assets, you would think
the Ford Foundation would want to do something other than fund
organizations intent on dividing Americans along racial and ethnic
lines. Yet Ford has been, and continues to be, the philanthropic
foundation most heavily involved in Hispanic advocacy politics.
<P>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
<a name="3">
<P>
<B>WHO DO FORD'S HISPANIC GROUPS REPRESENT?
</B><P>
Ford's decision to create political advocacy organizations was not
  needed by the Hispanic community,. Hispanic have never required
 exclusive ethnic-based mediating structures to serve their
interests.  Working-class Hispanics, for example, have often
preferred labor unions to represent them.  Mexican Americans and
other Hispanic groups serve in leadership positions in the Steelworkers,
United Auto Workers, Food and Commercial Workers, and other industrial
unions in the Midwest and Southwest, as well as in the United
Farm Workers union in California.  The executive vice-president
of the AFL-CIO, Linda Chavez-Thompson, is an Hispanic. 
<P>
Other Hispanics turn to the Catholic Church
to mediate their grievances, and there is a growing evangelical
Protestant ministry to Hispanics.  Many middle-class Hispanics
have joined local civic and business groups that target their
economic or social interests rather than their ethnicity.  In
addition, there are well-established organizations such as
the League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC).  Founded
in 1929, it is the nation's oldest Hispanic organization dedicated
to assimilation and integration into the larger American society.
 The American G.I. Forum is also an Hispanic group which represents
the needs of  veterans. These Hispanic groups typically pursue
assimilationist goals.  LULAC, for instance, lists the following
member duty in its declaration of purpose: &quot;To foster the
acquisition and facile use of the official language of our country
that we may thereby equip ourselves and our families for the fullest
enjoyment of our rights and privileges and the efficient discharge
of our duties and obligations to this, our country.&quot; Unfortunately,
by the 1970s, LULAC too had veered far to the left, and now is
almost no different from NCLR and MALDEF.
<P>
The original goals of assimilation seemed to suit the majority of Hispanics in 
America --but not the Ford Foundation.  Ford has pursued an agenda that separates 
Hispanics from other Americans and classifies them as a permanent underclass.
 The Ford Foundation instead attempts to copy the political strategies
of the black civil rights movement.  Relying on the advice of
a handful of Mexican American activists like Chicano academics
Julian Samora and Ernesto Galarza and political operator Herman
Gallegos, Ford in the 1960s decided to create new Hispanic institutions
to adopt an anti-assimilationist agenda and supplant the
traditional voices of the Hispanic community in America.
<P>
In its eagerness to mobilize social discontent,
the Ford Foundation has occasionally helped its operatives go
over the line that separates dissent from incitement to violence.
 In 1969, Jose Angel Gutierrez, founder of the La Raza Unida political
party in Texas, told a group of reporters at a press conference
that, &quot;We have got to eliminate the gringo, and what I mean
by that is if the worst comes to the worst, we have got to kill
him.&quot;  Gutierrez was affiliated with the Mexican America
Youth Organization (MAYO) which had received a $10,000 grant from
a Ford Foundation grantee.  Texas Democratic Congressman Henry
B. Gonzalez was so enraged by Gutierrez' rhetoric that he took
to the floor of the U.S. House of Representatives to accuse him
of promoting racial hatred.  Gonzalez attacked the Ford Foundation
for indirectly supporting La Raza Unida through its grant to MAYO.
<P>
Fearing that the incident would strengthen
efforts then underway in Congress to limit political advocacy
by tax-exempt foundations, Ford announced at the time that
MAYO was barred from receiving additional Ford money.  However,
some at Ford continued to defend Gutierrez.  For instance, Siobhan
Nicolau, the Ford Foundation program officer, contended that Gutierrez
was provoked to make the statement by hostile questions from the
press.
<P>
Despite incidents like these, Ford has not
been deterred from its commitment to establish extremely political
Hispanic advocacy organizations.  Whatever activists claim, Hispanic
Americans simply have not faced the same level of racial hostility
that African Americans have encountered, and their history in
this country is very different from that of Hispanics.
<P>
Although they have had their difficulties,
Hispanics have never faced the kind of political and legal discrimination
suffered by blacks.  Segregationist Jim Crow laws did not cover
Mexican Americans in the Southwest, for example.
<P>
And although de facto segregation of Hispanic
children existed in South Texas and to a lesser extent in California,
this segregation was not sanctioned by law and it was struck down
when challenged in the courts. As early as 1931 Hispanic parents
had won the right to send their children to school with non-Hispanics
-- even where local officials tried to prevent it.
<P>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
<a name="4">
<P>
<B>IN FORD'S DEEP POCKETS</B>
<P>
Despite these historical differences, Ford funds nonprofit
organizations that it hopes will recreate the black civil rights
movement for Hispanics. In 1968, it provided grants to ASPIRA,
the Spanish acronym for a New York City-based Puerto Rican education
group, allowing it to replicate its activities elsewhere.  ASPIRA
was instrumental in forcing New York City schools to test all
Hispanic children for placement in all-Spanish &quot;bilingual
education programs&quot; that claimed to be bilingual although
teaching in only one language -- Spanish.  The result of this mandatory
program has been that many non-Spanish speaking children
with Spanish surnames have been placed in Spanish language programs,
even if their parents wished the children to learn English. They
were segregated from the English speaking population. 
<P>
In 1972, Ford helped create the Puerto Rican
Legal Defense and Education Fund to mimic MALDEF's activities.
 In 1974, it provided operating funds for the Southwest Voter
Registration Education Project and later the Midwest Voter Registration
Education Project.  All of these shared Ford's segregation-oriented
priorities, rather than respond to the needs of an increasingly
assimilated Hispanic population.  
<P>
Other Hispanic organizations and programs
that have received large Ford Foundation grants include the National
Association of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials (NALEO)
Education Fund, the National Puerto Rican Coalition, and the Hispanic
Leadership Opportunity Program, which provides internships in
government agencies and public policy groups.  In addition, the
Ford Foundation has contributed to a number of academic programs
for Hispanics, including grants for Hispanic research to the City
University of New York, the University of Texas, and the University
of Michigan. Some of this reasarch has been legitimate scholarship.
 It was in 1963 that Ford funded a major UCLA study of Mexican
Americans. The &quot;Mexican American Study Project&quot; would
span five years and it involved field research in twenty cities.
 What resulted was an authoritative work on the history, demography,
institutions, and political participation of Mexican Americans:
 <I>The Mexican American People: The Nation's Second Largest Minority</I>,
by UCLA professors Leo Grebler, Joan Moore, and Ralph Guzman.
However, many of the more recent Ford-funded programs have been
politically tendentious rather than scholarly.
<P>
Other grantmaking foundations like Carnegie
and Rockefeller also fund Hispanic advocacy organizations as do
the philanthropic arms of corporations like Coors, Kellogg's,
Anheuser-Busch, BankAmerica and Pepsico.  The federal government
has also provided grants to Hispanic advocacy groups for job training
and other programs.  But neither the federal government nor any
other grantmaker has matched Ford in terms of long-term commitment
or amount of money contributed.  Indeed, the Ford Foundation has
virtually created the infrastructure of the contemporary Hispanic
policy movement.
<P>
With the support of the Ford Foundation, the
anti-assimilationist Hispanic organizations have scored notable
successes in politics and public relations at the expense of the
rich vitality and diversity of the community of Americans of Hispanic
origin. 
<P>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
<a name="5"><B>
<P>
PERPETUATING  STEREOTYPES</B>
<P>
Today, as a result of the efforts of the Ford Foundation,  in the
public mind and for all agencies of the U.S. government the
entire Hispanic American population is classified as a disadvantaged
minority group.  This encompasses the native-born and the recent
immigrant:  rich, white-European Argentine or Cuban Americans
as well as English-speaking blacks from Central America's
Caribbean coast.  It covers the Nahuatl-speaking Mexican
Indian and Peruvian-born descendants of Japanese immigrants to
South America.  For the purpose of political organization, it
makes no difference whether the &quot;Hispanic&quot; is a new
arrival or a citizen whose family has lived in the United States
for a dozen generations, descendants of holders of the Spanish
land grants covering millions of acres, or the head of the Coca-Cola
Corporation.
<P>
By linking disparate groups together and claiming
to represent them all, Hispanic organizations have been able to
acquire political power.  By promoting divisions between Hispanics
and non-Hispanics, they have maintained and strengthened
their power through &quot;divide and conquer&quot; tactics.  In
particular, they have encouraged the mind-set of the dependent
Hispanic &quot;victim&quot; _ something NCLR does especially well.
 Raul Yzaguirre, NCLR president, plays on these insecurities.
 He told the<I> Rocky Mountain News</I> this past summer:  &quot;The
bigotry and racism sweeping our country should be of concern not
just to minorities but to all Americans.  We will no longer tolerate
those in our society who fan the flames of this hatred to further
their careers or their political aspirations.&quot;
<P>
In 1994 Yzaguirre's inflamatory remarks were
reported in <I>Ethnic NewsWatch</I> published by a Hispanic news
group.  He told an Hispanic audience that &quot;every single federal
program and almost every public program discriminates against
Latinos.  That is not an accusation.  It's a fact.  Those realities
don't happen by accident.  Nobody else has less political power
in proportion to their numbers.&quot;
<P>
Yzaguirre also boasted of the increased political
clout Hispanic organizations like his could muster:  &quot;That
infrastructure has made it possible to have a rise in political
power. Now there are over five thousand elected Latino officials.
 <I>Hay orgullo.  Hay esperanza.</I>  We know we'll fulfill Walt
Whitman's prediction that Mexican Americans in the Southwest would
be the salvation of this country.&quot;
<P>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
<a name="6"><B>
<P>
THE AGENDA BEHIND FORD'S AGENDA
</B><P>
That MALDEF and NCLR understand the political importance of
dividing Americans this way is apparent in the kinds of public
policy issues they pursue most vigorously.  In immigration policy,
they ardently defend high levels of immigration and generous social
and safety net programs for immigrants.  Yet according to the
National Latino Political Survey, 75 percent of Mexican Americans
feel that there are too many immigrants in the U.S. now.  MALDEF
ignores the opinions of the people it claims to represent because
it knows that high levels of immigration serve its own purposes.
<P>
In areas like income and education, the continued
immigration of low-skilled and poorly-educated Hispanics
keeps general Hispanic achievement levels below that of non-Hispanic
whites.  This justifies the panoply of government programs that
advocacy groups say Hispanics want and need.  In fact, second
and third generation Hispanics are very much assimilated and enjoy
earnings and education levels comparable to non-Hispanics.
 On average, the weekly earnings of native-born Mexican American
men are about 83 percent those of non-Hispanic white men.
 When variables like schooling, experience, hours worked, and
geographical region of residence are taken into account, Mexican
American men earn about 93 percent of the weekly earnings of comparable
non-Hispanic white men.
<P>
Because Hispanics do not share any common
racial characteristics or national histories, political advocacy
groups like MALDEF and NCLR focus on language and culture to reinforce
a separate Hispanic ethnic identity.  With this goal in mind,
programs such as bilingual education become tools used to maintain
Hispanic language and culture and reduce the possibility of assimilation,
particularly among children.  By devaluing the importance of English
to American citizens, the bilingual ballot elevates Spanish and
makes it a quasi-official language.  These ballots are also used
to include Hispanics under the provisions of the Voting Rights
Act, which virtually guarantees ethnically-gerrymandered Hispanic
congressional districts. 
<P>
Because Hispanic organizations want to segregate
the community they claim to represent from the mainstream of America's
democracy, they hold in contempt all proposals to make English
the official language of the United States.  Yet significant numbers
of Hispanics do not agree.  The National Latino Political Survey
found in 1992 that well over 40 percent of Mexican Americans and
almost 50 percent of Puerto Ricans support legislation to make
English America's official language. That is significant support
for &quot;English Only.&quot;
<P>
Affirmative action, a program that richly
rewards racial and ethnic identity politics, is also used to divide
us.  Middle and upper-class Hispanics have always been assimilated
into mainstream American culture to a very great extent.  The
intermarriage rate between Hispanics and non-Hispanics, which
is almost 50 percent for Mexican Americans in California, is only
one indication of the effects of the process of assimilation.
 But ethnicity-based preferences and set-asides are a great incentive
for any group to identify itself by ethnicity.  Any group that
is offered preferential treatment in admission to universities,
jobs and job promotions, and non-competitive awards of government
contracts that pay well above the market rate is sure to take
advantage.  But it is also likely eventually to lose support from
the majority of those who receive no such privileges.  And the
genuine achievements of members of a politically-preferred ethnic
group will come under unfair suspicion. 
<P>
Nevertheless, over the past year the Ford
Foundation has distributed $1.4 million in grants to a dozen organizations
for litigation, research, and advocacy in favor of affirmative
action.  This year the Ford Foundation has contributed over $500,000
to several organizations specifically opposing California's Proposition
209, which is also known as the California Civil Rights Initiative.
 MALDEF launched legal challenges and a media campaign to defeat
the ballot initiative that would bar the state of California from
using race, ethnicity, or gender to discriminate against or grant
preferential treatment to any person or group.  No doubt, if the
measure passes, groups supported by the Ford Foundation will challenge
its constitutionality all the way to the Supreme Court.
<P>
The success or failure of this ballot proposition
to endure such challenges from Ford and its operatives will determine
whether America takes a step forward or backwards from equal opportunity
for all.
<P>
<BR>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
<P>
<BR>
<a name="7">
<H3>Georgie Anne Geyer's Americans No More: Is Citizenship Dead? 
</H3>
<H4>by Robert Huberty
</H4>
<P>
<I>Americans No More: The Death of Citizenship by Georgie Anne Geyer (Atlantic Monthly Press, 1996, 352 pages.) 
</I>
It is syndicated columnist Georgie Anne Geyer's thesis that the concept of citizenship has lost meaning for increasing numbers of Americans.
The civic bond that links Americans of all backgrounds by a committment to certain universal ideas of freedom and equality is unravelling. The
signs are everywhere, not least in the debate over how we decide who is an American. 
<P>
Geyer argues that the decline of citizenship has been hastened by political actions and economic developments that are driving us apart. At
home, politicians and advocacy groups are exploiting racial and ethnic conflict and are "retribalizing" communities to acquire political power.
This development is worldwide. In the former Yugoslavia, in India and Lebanon, and now in the U.S. politicians are making their careers by
demanding group rights and legal privileges for specific nationalities and subcultures. In America they are abetted by ethnic group advocacy
organizations that derive their support from private foundation grants and not from the ethnic groups they purport to represent. Geyer
describes how this process is fostering disunity in the name of diversity and only benefits those whose careers depend on it. As political and
media elites celebrate multiculturalism and denigrate individual merit and equal opportunity, the idea of a common American civic culture
atrophies. 
<P>
In contrast to domestic politics, U.S. economic institutions increasingly operate in a global marketplace. Politicians and government
bureaucrats are losing control over currency exchange rates, labor and capital markets, and the flow of information. Most conservatives
welcome this trend because it increases the power of the individual. But Geyer worries that globalization will make us less respectful of national laws and patriotic sentiments. American financial and government leaders will feel more at home dealing with their foreign counterparts over abstract issues than with the real problems of their fellow countrymen: No longer farmers and merchants in the town square, they will decide price changes and power shifts in conference calls at international airports between flights to high-level conferences. Officials of international agencies and nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) will also relax their national loyalties as they roam the world offering money and advice. Can such people recognize the tangible obligations and benefits of citizenship? 
<P>
In such a world what becomes of Americans who, as Tocqueville observed, join local associations to accomplish tasks without government
but with their neighbors? What will sustain citizens when the laws and institutions that guarantee equal opportunity are delegitimized at home
and displaced abroad? 
<P>
Geyer blames U.S. policymakers for letting special interest groups take the initiative in determining what new citizens and immigrants will think about America. As a journalist, she has roamed the country talking with scholars and public officials. Her interviews with those who are in charge of administering the laws regulating U.S. immigration and naturalization are especially revealing, and this reporting is the most valuable part of her book. 
<P>
For instance, Geyer reports in detail on the dumbed-down U.S. citizenship exams that the Immigration Act of 1990 now permits the nonprofit
Educational Testing Service (ETS) to administer. In place of requiring immigrants to give oral responses to questions posed by an Immigration
and Naturalization Service (INS) officer at a government office, officials say immigrants can choose to take a user-friendly ETS multiple choice test at a community center. And they can take the test as many times as they need to pass it. ETS proudly reports that it relies on a battery of Hispanic and refugee organizations like the Mexican American Legal Defense and and Education Fund (MALDEF) for advice on its testing policies and procedures. 
<P>
Instead of "Americanizing" new citizens, Geyer says ethnic advocacy groups are promoting a "reverse colonization" that would adapt our
citizenship to the ethnicity of the immigrant. Groups like MALDEF help immigrants become U.S. citizens without adequate knowledge of our
history, laws or language. They extract government entitlements for legal and illegal aliens, and raise obstacles to efforts to stop illegal
immigration. In lobbying over the content of civics in school textbooks and public ceremonies, ethnic advocacy groups too often sacrifice the ideas of the Founding Fathers to illiberal cultures of blood and soil. But most immigrants do not support their most strident demands. Surveys show that immigrants want to learn English quickly, to be assimilated to American culture, and to work and prosper. Far from being a cry of the people, MALDEF's legal briefs and the pronouncements of La Raza derive from the agenda of program officers at the Ford Foundation and other philanthropic grantmakers. Geyer's chapter on the Ford Foundation, excerpted in the National Review -- complemented by Linda Chavez and Jorge Amselle in this issue -- reviews the history of Ford's imposed revolution from above. 
<P>
Geyer's conclusion seems at odds with many of her findings. Apparently persuaded that Americans are throwing away their birthright and
overwhelmed by a sense of social breakdown, Geyer succumbs to emotions unsuited to the sharp reporting of her earlier chapters. She
describes the beauty of southern Wisconsin, where her family has a lakeside cottage, and compares it to an unlovely California marred by
criminal gangs, high taxes, overcrowding, gated communities, and illegal aliens. 
<P>
Instead of keeping her sights on the political and financial backers of ethnic political advocacy, she seems frightened by immigrants
themselves and appears to hold them responsible for the contrast that disturbs her. But America is more than southern Wisconsin, and the
type of political advocacy to which she objects would surely continue even without immigration. (If there were fewer universities, would
political correctness end?) 
<P>
Some argue that the alternative to the era of big government is big citizenship. Likewise, the alternative to the political demands of the ethnic
lobbies is to recognize and encourage the positive social achievements of immigrants. 
<P>
<BR>
<a href="#top">Table of Contents</a>
