<HTML>
<head>
<title>Hartman Press Release </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote>
<CENTER><H2>Center For Individual Rights</H2><BR>

<H3>1300 NINETEENTH STREET, N.W., SUITE 260<BR>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20036<BR><BR>
    
(202) 833-8400<BR>
FAX: (202) 833-8410<BR>
</CENTER><BR>
July 2, 1996<BR><BR>

For Immediate Release<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=+2><CENTER>Professor Claims Race and Sex <BR>
Based Discrimination Committed by Bowling Green</CENTER></FONT><BR>


<P>     Dr. John Hartman filed a lawsuit in federal court Tuesday claiming that he was denied employment at Bowling Green State University (BGSU) because of illegal discrimination.  He is suing the university and its accrediting agency--the Accrediting Council on Education in Journalism and Mass Communications (ACEJMC)--for sex and race based discrimination in violation of his equal protection rights.  Dr. Hartman is a white male.

<P>     In 1991, ACEJMC rescinded the journalism department's full accreditation, citing among the reasons for denial the perceived underrepresentation of women and minority faculty.  While the agency did not claim that BGSU had discriminated, it did require the department to eliminate the perceived imbalance in order to regain full accreditation.  BGSU's journalism department acceded to the ACEJMC's demands, and set-aside a number of future positions for women and minorities.

<P>     When Dr. Hartman applied for a teaching position at Bowling Green in 1994, his qualifications included a Ph.d in communication and twelve years teaching experience, as well as experience conducting seminars on mass communication and diversity, serving as a minority student mentor for several years, and publishing numerous scholarly works.  Despite his credentials, Bowling Green denied Dr. Hartman employment and instead offered the position to a black female who did not have a Ph.d, had significantly less teaching experience, and had a less impressive publishing record.

<P>     Following the hiring decision, Dr. Hartman filed a complaint with the Ohio Civil Rights Commission (OCRC).  OCRC found probable cause that the university had discriminated against Dr. Hartman, declaring that his "expertise and educational experience in the field of journalism more closely met the job requirements compared to the background of the successful candidate. . . ."  When subsequent mediation efforts between the parties failed, OCRC held a formal hearing in March on the issue, the results of which are pending.

<P>     In the lawsuit filed Tuesday, Dr. Hartman is seeking an injunction against the university and the accrediting agency which would prohibit them from discriminating against him on the basis of race and sex.  He is further seeking instatement to the position for which he was wrongfully denied employment, and damages resulting from the denial of employment.

<P>     Michael Rosman, attorney for Dr. Hartman and General Counsel for the Center for Individual Rights, stated that "Bowling Green and its accrediting agency created a system where, regardless of Dr. Hartman's qualifications, he could not have been hired simply because he is a white male.  It is precisely this sort of egregious deprivation of rights that the Equal Protection Clause prohibits."

<P>     To receive a copy of the complaint, or for more information about the case, call Robert Alt, Director of Public Relations and Education for the Center for Individual Rights, at 202-833-8400, ext. 101.
 
        

</blockquote>
<center><small><a href="/cir">CIR Home</a> | <a href="/cir/i-new.html">New</a> | <a href="/cir/about/contact.html">Contact</a></small></center><P>

</body>
