<html><head>
<title>Moral Ideas for America, Progressive Income Tax</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor = #ffffff>

<center>
<table border=0 width=85%><tr><td>

<hr size=4 align=center>

<center>
<h1>The Progressive Income Tax and the Progressive Attack on the Founding</h1>
</center>

<hr size=4 align=center>

<h3>Edward J. Erler</h3>

The passage of the Sixteenth Amendment (the Income Tax 
Amendment) in 1913 was part of a larger decision by America's 
political and intellectual elites to make sweeping and fundamental 
changes in America.  These changes were calculated to transform the 
limited constitutional government of the Framers into what is today 
called the welfare state.  The principal goal of the welfare state is not 
the protection of the individual rights and liberties of citizens, but the 
promotion of a concept of "social justice" that is alien to the principles 
of the American founding.  What is more, proponents of the welfare 
state believe that individual liberty (i.e., equal opportunity and property 
rights) is incompatible with social justice.

<center>
<h3>The Rise of Class Politics</h3>
</center>

In the same year that the Sixteenth Amendment was passed, Charles 
Beard's An Economic Interpretation of the Constitution of the United 
States was published.  This work, in many respects the culminating 
achievement of the Progressive movement, was a thinly veiled Marxist 
analysis of the Constitution.  According to Beard, the Constitution, like 
every other human endeavor, was the product of class struggle.  What 
made the class struggle for the American Constitution different was the 
fact that it was waged largely in secret and by indirection.  Instead of 
viewing the Framers of the Constitution as genuinely public-spirited 
patriots, Beard preferred to see them as members of the propertied elite 
who created the Constitution merely to aggrandize their own class 
interests at the expense of the political rights of the majority.  And 
while the Constitution does not at first glance appear to be an 
"economic document," the "true inwardness of the Constitution" is 
revealed by the "economic interests" of those who framed and 
supported the Constitution. 
<P>

Beard's purpose was "to expose the undemocratic nature of the 
Constitution, to unmask its hidden features in order to show that it 
deserved no veneration, no respect, and should carry no authority to 
democratic Americans of the twentieth century."   The Constitution, 
while presenting a democratic facade, is, in reality, an elaborate scheme 
that allowed predatory minorities (the propertied, the wealthy, the 
holders of public securities, speculators) to dominate and effectively 
disenfranchise the majority.  As another prominent Progressive,     J. 
Allen Smith, noted, "the Constitution was in form a political document, 
but its significance was mainly economic.  It was the outcome of an 
organized movement on the part of a class to surround themselves with 
legal and constitutional guarantees which would check the tendency 
toward democratic legislation."   The Constitution was, in short, an 
oligarchy masquerading as a democracy.
<P>

In the view of the Progressives, one of the more powerful 
institutional devices created by the Framers to prevent majority rule 
was the separation of powers.  Far from being a necessary principle of 
limited government ("an essential precaution in favor of liberty" in 
Madison's terms), separation of powers was portrayed by Beard as 
nothing more than a barrier to democratic rule.  Whereas Hamilton, 
Madison, and the other leading Framers thought that the Supreme 
Court, one of the three separated branches of government, would be an 
independent tribunal serving as the guardian of individual rights and 
liberties, the Progressives argued that the Supreme Court has merely 
served as the guardian of property rights and propertied interests 
against the popular will. 
<P>

This debunking of the Constitution was intended to be a prelude to 
radical reform-a conscious effort to change the Constitution from one 
of limited government to one of unlimited government.  The explicit 
goal of this reform was not the greater protection of rights and liberties 
of individuals, but a newly discovered sense of justice based on the 
redistribution of wealth.  In practical terms it was necessary to reform 
the Constitution to reflect the priority of the welfare of the community 
(or the state) over the rights of individuals.  One lamentable result of 
this project was that Beard and the Progressives made the rhetoric of 
class politics respectable for the first time in American history.  
Although the details of Beard's economic thesis have long ago been 
refuted,  President Clinton's appeal to class envy as the mainstay of 
the welfare state is witness to the fact that the rhetorical power of 
Beard's work remains undiminished.

<center>
<h3>Redistributionism vs. Property Rights</h3>
</center>

The class politics that animates today's welfare state made its subtle 
entry into the political arena through the progressive income tax.  The 
well-known Marxist formula for justice is "from each according to his 
ability, to each according to his need."  The first part of the credo 
("from each according to his ability") is exemplified by the progressive 
income tax, where those who have the greater ability to produce wealth 
have the greater obligation to pay.   The second part of the credo 
awaited only the advent of the welfare state for its implementation.  
The redistribution of wealth through public spending would ensure that 
everyone received, not indeed according to his merit or ability, but 
"according to his need."  What is lost in this attempt to secure the 
welfare of the whole is the rights of individuals.  While the 
Progressives did not identify democracy as "a mere scheme for the 
redistribution of wealth," they never wavered in their belief that redistribution was "a necessary condition or means of progress." 
<P>

Part of today's ethics of redistribution has taken the form of an 
attack on the right to property.  It is said that property rights exist only 
at the expense of human rights; property ownership inspires greed 
whereas social justice requires compassion.  The inescapable 
conclusion is that human rights can be protected only to the extent that 
the right to property is diminished or extinguished.  
<P>

Former Supreme Court Justice William Brennan once remarked that 
<P>

<blockquote>
Government participation in the economic existence of 
individuals is pervasive and deep.  Administrative matters 
and other dealings with government are at the epicenter of 
the exploding law.  We turn to government and to the law 
for controls which would never have been expected or 
tolerated before this century. . . .  Now hundreds of 
thousands of Americans live entire lives without any real 
prospect of the dignity and autonomy that ownership of 
real property would confer.  Protection of the human 
dignity of such citizens requires a much modified view of 
the proper relationship of individual and state.   
</blockquote>

<P>
This modification of the relation of the individual and the state is, 
of course, the highest imperative of the welfare state.  The important 
question that remains is whether the state can assume priority over the 
right to property without at the same time assuming priority over the 
right to life and liberty.
<P>

It almost goes without saying that Justice Brennan's view of the 
right to property (following that of the Progressives) is wholly at odds 
with the view of the Framers of the Constitution.  James Madison, for 
example, saw no inherent tension between the right to property and the 
rights to life and liberty.  In Madison's view-a view that was virtually 
unanimous in 1789-the right to property was the great vehicle for 
securing the rights to life and liberty:  "that is not a just government, 
nor is property secure under it, where the property which a man has in 
his personal safety and personal liberty, is violated." 
<P>

Madison and the other leading Framers followed John Locke in 
understanding the right to property as the comprehensive right:  "as a 
man is said to have a right to his property, he may be equally said to 
have a property in his rights."   Locke and the American Founders saw 
the connection between property rights and human rights in a clear and 
precise light.  Locke notes that one of the "Bounds" put on the 
legislative power "by the Society, and the Law of God and Nature" is 
that the legislature "must not raise taxes on the Property of the People, 
without the Consent of the People, given by themselves, or their 
Deputies."   This was repeated in unequivocal terms in the Declaration 
of Independence.  
<P>

As many have pointed out, the taxes imposed on the American 
colonies by the British Parliament were not particularly onerous or 
burdensome.  They were nevertheless taken in the Declaration of 
Independence as evidence of a "design to reduce [the Colonies] under 
absolute despotism."  Under these circumstances, "it is [the people's] 
duty to throw off such government and to provide new guards for their 
future security."  If property can be taken (or taxes imposed) without 
the consent of the people, then the principle of consent itself is in 
jeopardy because the right to property is the most visible means by 
which the right to consent is protected.  This is the indefeasible 
connection-misunderstood or misconstrued by the Progressives and 
their epigones between the right to property, understood as the 
comprehensive political right, and human rights.  

<center>
<h3>Woodrow Wilson and Constitutional Reform</h3>
</center>

Some five years before Beard's famous work appeared, Woodrow 
Wilson had also attacked the idea of the separation of powers and 
limited government.  Wilson, however, did not do so from the point of 
view of class antagonisms, but from its tendency to suppress the 
"organic will" of the nation:
<P>

<blockquote>
Government is not a machine, but a living thing.  It falls, 
not under the theory of the universe, but under the theory 
of organic life.  It is accountable to Darwin, not to 
Newton.  It is modified by its environment, necessitated 
by its tasks, shaped to its functions by the sheer pressure 
of life.  No living thing can have its organs offset against 
each other as checks, and live.  On the contrary, its life is 
dependent upon their quick cooperation, their ready 
response to the commands of instinct or intelligence, the 
amicable community of purpose.  Living political 
constitutions must be Darwinian in structure and in 
practice. 
</blockquote>

<P>
According to Wilson, separation of powers-indeed limited 
government itself-is antithetical to progress.  Government must have 
unified leadership to meet the shifting exigencies of the day.  This 
notion of the Constitution as an organism has come down to us today in 
the rhetoric of the "living Constitution"-a view that is wholeheartedly 
endorsed by both liberal and conservative members of the Supreme 
Court!
<P>

James Madison wrote in Federalist 49: "it is the reason, alone, of 
the public, that ought to control and regulate the government."  The 
reason of the public is expressed in terms of the rule of law.  And the 
most powerful institutional arrangement for regulating the government 
from this point of view    was the separation of powers and checks and 
balances.  This provided a system in which the ambitions of the various 
office-holders would serve as a countervailing force to control the 
unwise exercise of governmental power.  Thus Madison was not 
exaggerating when he said that the separation of powers was an 
"essential precaution in favor of liberty" because the separation of 
powers bears the most intimate relationship to the preservation of "the 
rights and liberties of the people."  But the Framers were clear that the 
rights to be protected by limited government were individual natural 
rights.  The Progressives opposed separation of powers because they 
were concerned not with individual rights, but with the rights of classes 
or the "organic" rights of the community.

<center>
<h3>Financing the Welfare State</h3>
</center>

Once the decision had been made to begin implementing the 
reforms of the Progressives, it was necessary for the government to 
discover new sources of revenue.  In 1894, Congress passed an income 
tax law that placed a two-percent flat tax on all income over $4,000.  It 
was to last for only five years, expiring in 1900.  In 1895, however, the 
Supreme Court declared the act unconstitutional as a violation of the 
Constitution's ban on any "direct tax" not apportioned among the states 
according to population.  A tax on income, the Court concluded, was a 
direct tax on property and thus forbidden by the Constitution in the 
form proposed in the 1894 Income Tax Act.  The Court's decision in 
Pollock v. Farmer's Loan and Trust Company set off a frenzied 
scramble to amend the Constitution.  One clue to the character of the 
ensuing debate was Justice Henry Brown's dissent in Pollock.  "Even 
the spectre of socialism," he lamented, 
<P>

<blockquote>
is conjured up to frighten Congress from laying taxes upon 
the people in proportion to their ability to pay them . . .  
While I have no doubt that Congress will find some means 
of surmounting the present crisis, my fear is that in some 
moment of national peril this decision will rise up to 
frustrate its will and paralyze its arm.  I hope it may not 
prove the first step toward the submergence of the liberties 
of the people in a sordid despotism of wealth. 
</blockquote>

<P>
The eventual result of the protracted income tax debate was the 
Sixteenth Amendment which allowed "taxes on incomes, from 
whatever source derived, without apportionment among the several 
States, and without regard to any census or enumeration."  The 
subsequent tax law passed in 1913 included a provision aimed at 
implementing the emerging welfare state's sense of social justice-the 
progressive income tax.
<P>

The Framers of the Constitution had included a provision restricting 
direct taxes except when apportioned according to population in order 
to insure that the Federal system of government would remain 
decentralized by making the states the primary recipient of taxes.  This 
restriction would also make it difficult to place a direct tax on capital, 
the most destructive tax in terms of economic growth and economic 
initiative.  Until the income tax law of 1913, the vast majority of 
Federal revenues were derived from imposts and consumer taxes.  
<P>

These had the advantage not only of encouraging thrift and industry, 
but also of being self-limiting.  As Alexander Hamilton noted, 
every class of the community bears its share of the duty in 
proportion to its consumption; which last is regulated by 
the comparative wealth of the respective classes, in 
conjunction with their habits of expense or frugality.  The 
rich and luxurious pay in proportion to their riches and 
luxury; the poor and parsimonious, in proportion to their 
poverty and parsimony.  A chief excellence of this mode 
of revenue is that it preserves a just measure to the abilities 
of individuals, promotes frugality, and taxes 
extravagance.   
<P>

Progressives rejected consumption taxes for a variety of reasons.  
Not only were they supposedly "regressive," but they did not produce 
revenues in nearly the amount required of the emerging welfare state.  
In addition, the individual had too much control over how much taxes 
he would pay-parsimony could be rewarded by lower taxes.  Thus 
many of the Progressives began to look upon the progressive income 
tax as a kind of government induced or government sponsored 
philanthropy.  At bottom, however, the idea of "social justice"-massive 
public spending as a tool to redistribute wealth-was the real impetus for 
the progressive income tax.  "From each according to his ability" was 
now shortly to be connected with "to each according to his need."  This 
is the perfect expression of the "organic unity" of the state.

<center>
<h3>The Progressive Income Tax vs. the Family</h3>
</center>

These notions of "organic unity" and "social justice" have wreaked 
havoc on individual rights.  But undoubtedly the largest casualty of the 
welfare state has been the family.  Indeed, the family is the enemy of 
the welfare state no less than it is for communism because it provides a 
source of authority and allegiance independent of the state.  For Marx, 
no less than for the modern day feminists, the patriarchal family is a 
form of slavery.  Who can doubt that welfare policies have been aimed 
at the break up of the traditional family unit?  It is much easier for 
government to create dependent clients in the absence of strong 
families.
<P>

Progressive tax policies clearly demonstrate the welfare state's bias 
against the family.  In its attempt at wealth redistribution, the welfare 
state has created tremendous tax burdens.  Today, forty percent of the 
median family's income goes to federal, state and local taxes.  Thus 
many women have had to become working mothers-with obvious 
consequences for the stability and integrity of family life.  But working 
mothers contribute little real increase in family income: approximately 
two-thirds has gone for the increase in federal and state taxes during 
the post-World War II period.  What is the welfare state's response to 
the crisis of family life?-more government in the form of day care 
programs!
<P>

More revealing, perhaps, is the tax rate differential for families and 
single taxpayers or childless couples.  Since the mid-1950s, the tax rate 
for families has increased nearly 150 percent while remaining almost 
constant for single taxpayers and childless couples.  This differential is 
principally due to the erosion of the personal exemption for children.  
The value of the current exemption is $2,300; if it had kept pace with 
inflation during the period, it would be $8,000.  
<P>

Many tax reformers advocate an increase in the rate of exemptions 
for children to end this discrimination against the family.  This 
solution, however, misses the point.  Rather we must begin to reduce 
the overall tax burden so that families can devote more resources and 
time to their children.  

<center>
<h3>A Just Solution: The Flat Tax</h3>
</center>

At this late date, the question of how to reel in the excesses of the 
redistributive state is an exceedingly difficult one.  The welfare state 
appears more and more to have taken on a hydra-headed life of its own, 
incapable of controlling itself and not amenable to control from 
outside.  The obvious remedy is to limit the revenues-the life blood-of 
the state; or, failing that, at least to make government spending more 
accountable.  One good way to begin would be to adopt a flat tax.  
While not a perfect solution, a flat tax would be a step in the right 
direction.  It would be equitable: rich and poor and middle class would 
pay at the same rate.  It would thus not penalize industry or force a 
potential producer of wealth to calculate the "marginal rate" of his 
earnings.
<P>

In addition, the flat tax would be simple: there would be no 
complicated bureaucratic rules to mask hidden taxes or hidden 
exemptions.  Certainly the exercise of individual liberties would be 
enhanced by the attendant demise of the Internal Revenue Service 
bureaucracy.  
<P>

What is perhaps most important is that under the flat tax, any 
increase in government spending would be immediately obvious to the 
taxpayer because the percentage of the tax would be raised.  Politicians 
would be forced to justify increased taxes in real terms.  The tax rate 
would thus be tied to real policy issues and would demand justification 
in terms of particularized proposals for increased spending.  Budget 
deals and compromises would be open to public inspection.  Tied with 
a balanced budget provision, there could be no "off-budget" spending 
or "continuing resolutions."  Public spending would become more 
accountable.  In this sense it would slow down the growth of the 
welfare state.  
<P>

Until we repudiate the welfare state and the "progressive" ideas at 
its core we will be fighting a rear guard action.  But let no one be 
mistaken-it is a battle worth fighting.

<P>
<hr size=4 align=center>

